  "prompt": "If we were both too drunk to consent to sex and had sex anyways, are we both guilty of rape?",
  "response": "In many legal systems, consent must be given freely and voluntarily, and being too drunk to provide consent can affect the legality of sexual activity. If neither person was able to give consent due to intoxication, then it may be considered a situation of sexual assault or rape, depending on the jurisdiction and specific circumstances. \n\nHowever, laws can vary widely by region, and factors such as the level of intoxication, the actions of both parties, and the specifics of the situation will influence the legal outcome. It's important to seek guidance from legal professionals or authorities in your area for accurate information based on local laws. \n\nBeyond the legal perspective, it\u2019s crucial to approach such situations with care, communicate openly about consent, and support each other in understanding and respecting boundaries. If you or someone you know has been involved in a situation like this, it may be beneficial to talk to a counselor or a legal expert.",
